Patient: What should I eat to help with my heart failure?
Healthcare Educator: Focus on fresh fruits, vegetables, lean meats, and whole grains. Limit processed and fried foods.

Patient: Can I still eat fried chicken?
Healthcare Educator: It's best to avoid fried foods. Choose grilled or baked chicken instead.

Patient: Is there a limit for how much salt I can have?
Healthcare Educator: Yes, try to limit your sodium intake to less than 1500mg per day.

Patient: What about drinking alcohol?
Healthcare Educator: Limit alcohol to moderation. Too much can raise your blood pressure.

Patient: Can I still have my morning coffee?
Healthcare Educator: Yes, but limit to one or two cups. Too much caffeine can raise your heart rate.

Patient: Are there any fruits or vegetables I should avoid?
Healthcare Educator: All fruits and vegetables are good. But avoid canned ones because they often contain added salt.

Patient: Can I eat cheese?
Healthcare Educator: Choose low-sodium cheeses. High-sodium foods can make heart failure worse.

Patient: What about whole grains? Why are they important?
Healthcare Educator: Whole grains are high in fiber. They help lower cholesterol and keep your heart healthy.

Patient: Can I still have my favorite dessert, chocolate cake?
Healthcare Educator: Desserts are fine in moderation. But choose dark chocolate, it's better for your heart.

Patient: Is there any food that can help improve my heart health?
Healthcare Educator: Yes, fish like salmon and mackerel are rich in omega-3 fatty acids, which are good for heart health.